{"/service/ndnp/mohi/batch_mohi_franklin_ver01/data/sn89066651/00211109476/1913060501/1085.xml":{"full_text":"Think It Over.\nTo Tin: Businicss Mkn op\nHayti: Whi'ii we started this\npaper, nearly five years ago, Hay\nti had no paper, and we under\ntook the labor with the under\n.standi nn that we were to receive\na liberal .supiort. For the past\nthree years, however, since the\nreturn of prosperity this paper\nsacrificed its own best interests\nand cut its own throat to bring\nto your town, we have con\nducted the paper largely at our\nown expense and with what pat\nronage we could draw from Ca\nruthersville and other towns, and\niit the same time we have em\nployed labor cheap and worked\nday and night and Sunday to get\nout a credible paper. Now,\nthere is going to be a change,\n:uid one that we have been figur\ning on for many months. We do\nnot believe we have a subscriber\noutside of the Hayti list bub who\ntakes the Herald on account of\nhis personal feeling for the edi\ntor. The two county seat and\nlocal option lights have incensed\nthe people of the county against\nour city, but not against us. On\naccount of our lairness and hon\nesty of purpose we have grown\nin public favor, but not until the\npast few months did we win the\ntavor due us, and as we win out\nside favor and support, our home\nsupport grows less and less.\nWhy, we are powerless to under\nstand. Our C'aruthersville list is\nnext to Hayti. Our Kennett,\n(Jape Girardeau and St. Louis\nlists are larger than any outside\nof Caruthersville and Hayti. We\ndo not believe it would be possi\nble, if we should move, for a new\nman to start a new paper. What\nare you going to do about it?\nMrs. J. A. Johnson returned\nfrom Kaskaskia, 111., on Monday\nof last week, where she had been\ncalled to attend the funeral of\nher brother, J. L. Peeruian, who\ndied the 13th of May.\nLeo Greenwoll left Thursday\nnight for St. Louis, to accompa\nny his father-in-law, J. O. Tins\nley, to French Lick Springs. Mr.\nTinsley han been in ill health for\nsome time.\nMr. and Mrs. A. J. Dorris\ncame up from Blytheville Friday\nand returned Saturday. Mr.\nDorris has a large store here,\nand is in the furniture business\nat Blytheville.\nMilch Cow For Sale Good condi\ntioned and a goad cow. II. Linjji\nnmnn, 3 miles south of Hiiyti. 3U-LH\nFire! That reminds us of the\nconnundrum: \"Why was Umbil\nlicus Lacey's famous affidavit is\nsued at midnight belore the re\ncent city election at Caruthers-\nV\"\nCemetery Notice.\nNotice Is hereby piven that ut the\nregular meeting of the Board of Al\ndermen Monday nltfht, Juno 2, a reso\nlution wui adopted, appointing and\nsetting aside Tuesday, Juno 17, as a\nday for cleaning up, improving, beau\ntify ing and decorating Woodlawn\nOmeterj\nAll who feel an interest in the city's\nburying ground and especially all\nwho have relative and friends bur\niiid theie, aru urgently requested to\ncomo and show this tribute of respect\nto the departed.\nWe want to make this cemetery a\nbeautiful plncn, remove all stumps\nand undergrowth, plow and- grade\nthe grounds, round up and pave the\ndriveways, and th walkways\nConntrv people are especially urg-1\ned to bring teams, stump pullers,\nplows and harrows, and theeitv peo\nple to bring what available tools they\nhae. i\nThe Maxorand Hoard of Aldermen\nespeeiulh tirgt- you to come and lend\na helping hand.\na gasoline engine\nit back-fired.\" .losh\nville like\n\"Because\nWiser.\n.Tas. M. Wilson of Kennett, the\nhead man for this district in the\nState Fish and Game Depart\nment, was in this city Thur.siiay\nand Saturday night, looking alter\nhis duties.\nB. H. Deweese has lost a cow,\ndescribed as follows: 2 under\nbits in each ear; branded B on\nright hip; red; -1 years old; left\nfore teat smaller than others.\nPlease report to owner.\nMrs. A. E. Taylor and baby\ncame up from Little Roc If, Ark.,\nSaturday night, to join Mr. Tay\nlor. Mrs. Carrie Trainor of Piggott,\nArk., came over Monday, to visit\nher mother, Mr.s. Dan Nunn.\nTIM j DORRIS f SALOON\nI have been in the saloon business for 45 years, and the fact\nthat I am still in the business is sufficient proof and guai\nantee of my square dealing and of the quality of my goods.\na f\"e:a brand\nOld Lynch Itye. Lynch Special. Lynch Special Hurbon\nHappy. lack. American Pride. Kentuckv Tiuern.\nMonarch of the West. Premium He. Dry Hun\nWines, Brandies, Gins, Peach and Honey, Kock and Rye, etc.\nOut of town trade and mail orders a specialty. Try us.\nHAYTI,\nMISSOURI\nHOWDY\nMr. and Mrs. Buyer:\nThis is our bow lo you. We\nhave engaged this space in the Hayti\nHerald solely for your benefit, so that\nwe can tell you each week what we\nhave to offer in the way of merchandise.\nDry Goods\nClothing\nShoes, Hats\nLadies Ready-to-Wear Goods\nFurniture\nCarpets\nRugs\nArt Squares, Mattings, etc.\nand many other articles too numerous\nto mention.\nWATCH THIS SPACE\nA. J. DORRIS\nIf our ex bos, Uubillieus Ii\neey of the Anti-Democrat, could\nhave focused his liodalc on\nthat section of levee he told hi\nreaders, floated down the river\nduring the overflow with a regi\nment ol soldier?-on it, he would\nnot need to panhandle the county\nofficers for legal advertising.\n.losh Wiser.\nLouis Patterson of druthers\nville is now attending to the tele\nphone lines in this city, which is\nsufficient guarantee that this\nend of the business will be well\ntaken care of.\nDavid Smitherman of MeHaine\nsends us a dollar for the renewal\nof his subscription. David is one\nof our home boys and we are\nglad to see him doing well.\nRiley Summers is preparing\nto build a brick business house\nadjoining the Spencer Stubbs\ndepartment of the Fred Morgan\nbuilding.\nSome peopl\" c.mnot stand\nprosperity. Hence, every time\nHayti gets a start, they attempt\nto kill its progress.\nMiss Gladys Clark of Sum\nmertsworth, New Hampshire,\nwho visited her uncle, H. M.\nRansburgh, a few days last week,\nreturned home Saturday night.\nMiss Hazel Ransburgh of New\nMadrid, who has been visiting\nher uncle, II. M. Ransburgh\nat this place, returned homo\nMonday,\nJudge .7. S. Gossom, Col. A. L.\nOliver and Wm. C. Wilks attend\ned to legal business before our\njustice courts Monday.\nJoe Foust was here from Con\ncord Satu rday.\nD. L. Sorrell of Wolf Bayou\nvisited in Hayti Sunday.\nCall for a bottle of Tip Top, Letup\nBpecial brew. I\nEverybody who uses whiskey\nshould ubo the best. It ia not so like\nly to make you drunk, loaves no bad\nelTect, Ih better for your health anil I\nwill make you feel good. You can'\nt;et it at Fred MorpatiB Saloon. 20\nCall for a bottle ot Tip Top, Letup's\nlatest and best special brew. I\nAll the best and latest in drinks, at\n'roil Morgan's saloon. Or if you\nw:ni whiskey, wine or beer for your'\nfamily or for medicine, the stock is.\nIhrue and you can jret what you call I\nfor. '.'Otf I\nConstable J. W. Stout of Pas\ncola attended to legal business\nin this city Monday.\nJ. E. McFall will leave next\nTuesday to spend a few days in\nMemphis.\nLansing Bettis of Dell, Ark.,\nvisited in Hayti Sunday and\nMonday.\nD. D. Harbert was in Steele\nThursday.\nMrs. Ethalinda Daley has\nmoved from Wardell to this city.\nFred Hud gens of Dry Bayou\ni was a Hayti visitor Saturday.\nJake Williams was here from\nDry Bayou Saturday.\nHolland Advertiser: If boy\ncotting serves all country news\npapers like the boycott inaugur\nated against the Hayti Herald,\nwe would be glad to have the Ad\nvertiser boycotted long enough\nto fill it up with good paying ads\nand get a big bunch of subscrib\ner, anyhow. Judging by the\nnumber of new advertisements\nthat paper is carrying, the boy\ncott seems to help instead of in\njure. Chns. Law of Boynton, Ark,\nvisited his brother, Sam, in this\ncity. Monday.\nMrs John Scott visited in C.i\nruthersville a few days last week.\nSCHOOL PROGRAM\nBy the Grades\nCITY HALL\nFRIDAY NIGHT. JUNE 6\nMONEY REFUNDED\nWITH A SMILE.\nLeading Drug Store Will Give Mon\ney Back Should T